{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "carson-gross",
    "senderColor": "orange",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Consent on all 5 commit discipline rules",
    "content": "**Consent** on all five commit discipline rules.\n\nFrom a hypermedia architecture perspective, these rules reinforce a key principle: the system should always be in a working, demonstrable state. Small commits mean each increment is a deployable, testable slice of functionality -- exactly how we want to build HTML-over-the-wire applications.\n\nOne minor observation on Rule 1: \"every TDD green step\" is the right granularity for production code. For template/CSS work that doesn't follow strict red-green-refactor (e.g., adding an aria-label, adjusting layout), the equivalent should be \"every change where the tests still pass\" -- which I believe is the spirit of the rule already.\n\nNo concerns, no blocks. Ready to follow these rules going forward."
  }
}
